      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lazio's Abortion Stance</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gerald D Scorse letter letter holds it is inconsistent and hypocritical for Repr Rick A Lazio to say he upholds abortion rights but opposes public financing of abortion (May 25 news article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Abortion Rights Group Is Set to Endorse Mrs. Clinton'' (news article, May 25): It is inconsistent and hypocritical for Representative Rick A. Lazio to say he upholds abortion rights but opposes public financing of abortion.</p>
        <p>A right is real only so much as it is available; to deny public financing is to deny abortion rights to those who need them most. Mr. Lazio's position is reminiscent of the pre-Roe v. Wade days when abortion, while illegal in most states, was always available to those who could pay for it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Abortion Rights Group Is Set to Endorse Mrs. Clinton'' (news article, May 25): It is inconsistent and hypocritical for Representative Rick A. Lazio to say he upholds abortion rights but opposes public financing of abortion.</p>
        <p>A right is real only so much as it is available; to deny public financing is to deny abortion rights to those who need them most. Mr. Lazio's position is reminiscent of the pre-Roe v. Wade days when abortion, while illegal in most states, was always available to those who could pay for it.</p>
        <p>In the year 2000, however, this is no longer the true meaning of abortion rights.</p>
        <p>GERALD E. SCORSE  New York, May 25, 20001</p>
      </block>
